  "prompt": "What is the best way to simplify [math]\\frac{x-\\frac{1}{x}}{1+\\frac{1}{x}}[/math] where defined?",
  "response": "To simplify the expression:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{x - \\frac{1}{x}}{1 + \\frac{1}{x}}\n\\]\n\n**Step 1: Eliminate the Fractions**\n\nMultiply both the numerator and the denominator by \\( x \\) (assuming \\( x \\neq 0 \\)) to eliminate the fractions:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{x \\left( x - \\frac{1}{x} \\right)}{x \\left( 1 + \\frac{1}{x} \\right)} = \\frac{x^2 - 1}{x + 1}\n\\]\n\n**Step 2: Factor the Numerator**\n\nNotice that the numerator \\( x^2 - 1 \\) is a difference of squares and can be factored:\n\n\\[\nx^2 - 1 = (x + 1)(x - 1)\n\\]\n\nSo the expression becomes:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{(x + 1)(x - 1)}{x + 1}\n\\]\n\n**Step 3: Simplify by Cancelling Common Terms**\n\nAssuming \\( x + 1 \\neq 0 \\) (i.e., \\( x \\neq -1 \\)), we can cancel \\( x + 1 \\) from the numerator and the denominator:\n\n\\[\nx - 1\n\\]\n\n**Final Simplified Expression:**\n\n\\[\nx - 1 \\quad \\text{(where } x \\neq 0 \\text{ and } x \\neq -1\\text{)}\n\\]\n\n**Summary:**\n\n\\[\n\\frac{x - \\frac{1}{x}}{1 + \\frac{1}{x}} = x - 1 \\quad \\text{for} \\quad x \\neq 0 \\text{ and } x \\neq -1\n\\]",
